---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "How do I know if my components are compatible?",
    a: "The most important compatibility checks are: CPU socket matching the motherboard, RAM type (DDR4 vs DDR5) matching the motherboard, case size supporting your motherboard form factor (ATX, Micro-ATX, Mini-ITX) and GPU length, and ensuring your power supply has enough wattage for your CPU and GPU combined."
  },
  {
    q: "Is it better to build or buy a prebuilt PC?",
    a: "Building your own PC is generally better as it offers higher quality components for the same price, complete customization, and teaches you how to maintain and upgrade your system in the future. Prebuilts are convenient but often compromise on power supply, motherboard, or RAM quality to hit a price point."
  },
  {
    q: "Do I need an aftermarket CPU cooler?",
    a: "If you are buying a high-end CPU (like an Intel Core i7/i9 or AMD Ryzen 7/9), an aftermarket cooler is required as they rarely include stock coolers and run very hot. For budget CPUs (like Ryzen 5 or Core i3/i5), the included stock cooler is usually adequate, though an aftermarket one will be quieter and keep temps lower."
  },
  {
    q: "How much RAM do I need for gaming in 2026?",
    a: "16GB is the bare minimum for modern gaming, but 32GB is quickly becoming the new standard. With 32GB, you can comfortably play the most demanding AAA titles while having Discord, Spotify, and browser tabs open in the background without stuttering."
  },
  {
    q: "What should I do after building my PC?",
    a: "First, enter the BIOS and enable XMP/EXPO to ensure your RAM runs at its advertised speed. Then, install Windows using a USB drive. Once in Windows, run Windows Update, install your motherboard chipset drivers, install your graphics card drivers directly from NVIDIA/AMD, and finally, download a game to test your temperatures and performance."
  }
];

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Best PC Building Guide 2026",
    "description": "The ultimate step-by-step guide to building a gaming PC in 2026. Covers budget tiers, component selection, AM5 vs LGA1700, compatibility, assembly, and BIOS setup.",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "Leeroy Jenkins"
    },
    "datePublished": "2026-06-15",
    "dateModified": "2026-06-15"
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": faqs.map(f => ({
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": f.q,
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": f.a
      }
    }))
  }
];

export const meta = {
  title: "Best PC Building Guide 2026 — Step-by-Step Tutorial",
  description: "The ultimate step-by-step guide to building a gaming PC in 2026. Covers budget tiers, component selection, AM5 vs LGA1700, compatibility, assembly, and BIOS setup.",
  category: "guide",
  published: "2026-06-15",
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="leeroyjenkins"
  title="Best PC Building Guide 2026 — Step-by-Step Tutorial"
  description="The ultimate step-by-step guide to building a gaming PC in 2026. Covers budget tiers, component selection, AM5 vs LGA1700, compatibility, assembly, and BIOS setup."
  canonical="https://leeroyjenkins.quest/pc-building-guide"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>The Ultimate PC Building Guide (2026)</h1>
      <p>Everything you need to know to build your perfect gaming PC, from selecting components to the final power-on and benchmarking.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">
      <p>Building your own PC is a rewarding experience that gives you complete control over your system's aesthetics, performance, and budget. While it might seem intimidating at first, modern PC building is often described as "Lego for adults." Components are designed to fit together easily, and as long as you follow a few basic rules, you'll be gaming on a rig you built yourself in no time.</p>

      <h2>1. Recommended Build Tiers (2026)</h2>
      <p>Before buying parts, you need a budget. Here are three modern build tiers to guide your purchasing decisions.</p>

      <div class="tier-grid">
        <div class="tier-card">
          <h3>The $600 Budget Build</h3>
          <p>Perfect for 1080p gaming and esports titles. You'll make some compromises on visual settings in AAA games, but it offers a solid entry point.</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>CPU:</strong> AMD Ryzen 5 5600 or Intel Core i3-13100F</li>
            <li><strong>GPU:</strong> AMD Radeon RX 7600 or NVIDIA RTX 4060</li>
            <li><strong>RAM:</strong> 16GB DDR4-3200</li>
            <li><strong>Storage:</strong> 1TB PCIe 3.0 NVMe SSD</li>
            <li><strong>Focus:</strong> Maximize GPU budget; stick to reliable, cheaper DDR4 platforms.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="tier-card highlight">
          <h3>The $1200 Mid-Range Sweet Spot</h3>
          <p>The ideal balance of price to performance. Excellent for high-refresh-rate 1440p gaming and solid future-proofing.</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>CPU:</strong> AMD Ryzen 5 7600X or Intel Core i5-14400F</li>
            <li><strong>GPU:</strong> AMD Radeon RX 7800 XT or NVIDIA RTX 4070 SUPER</li>
            <li><strong>RAM:</strong> 32GB DDR5-6000</li>
            <li><strong>Storage:</strong> 2TB PCIe 4.0 NVMe SSD</li>
            <li><strong>Focus:</strong> Moving to modern DDR5 platforms for longevity; strong 1440p capability.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="tier-card">
          <h3>The $2500 High-End Battlestation</h3>
          <p>No compromises. Built for stunning 4K gaming, heavy video editing, and pushing the absolute maximum framerates possible.</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>CPU:</strong> AMD Ryzen 7 7800X3D or Intel Core i7-14700K</li>
            <li><strong>GPU:</strong> NVIDIA RTX 4080 SUPER or AMD Radeon RX 7900 XTX</li>
            <li><strong>RAM:</strong> 32GB or 64GB DDR5-6000 CL30</li>
            <li><strong>Storage:</strong> 4TB PCIe 4.0/5.0 NVMe SSD</li>
            <li><strong>Focus:</strong> Top-tier cooling, premium aesthetics, and massive performance.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>2. Component Selection Guide</h2>
      <p>Understanding what each part does will help you allocate your budget effectively.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>CPU (Processor):</strong> The brain of your PC. For gaming, single-core speed often matters more than having tons of cores. Don't overspend here at the cost of your GPU unless you do heavy productivity work.</li>
        <li><strong>GPU (Graphics Card):</strong> The most important component for gaming performance. This is what renders your games. Aim to spend 35-50% of your total budget on the GPU alone.</li>
        <li><strong>RAM (Memory):</strong> Your system's short-term memory. 16GB is the minimum, 32GB is recommended for 2026. Pay attention to speed (MHz) and latency (CL).</li>
        <li><strong>Motherboard:</strong> Connects everything together. Ensure it has the right socket for your CPU and the features you need (like built-in WiFi, enough USB ports, or M.2 slots).</li>
        <li><strong>Storage (SSD):</strong> Always use an NVMe M.2 SSD for your boot drive and main games. They are vastly faster than older SATA SSDs and hard drives.</li>
        <li><strong>PSU (Power Supply):</strong> Do not cheap out here! A bad power supply can destroy your entire system. Buy from reputable brands (Corsair, Seasonic, EVGA) and ensure you have enough wattage (e.g., 750W or 850W for mid-to-high-end builds).</li>
        <li><strong>Case & Cooler:</strong> Ensure your case has good airflow (look for mesh front panels) and that your CPU cooler can handle your processor's heat output.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>3. Platform Comparison: AM5 vs. LGA1700</h2>
      <p>Choosing your CPU means choosing a motherboard platform. In 2026, the two main choices are AMD's AM5 and Intel's LGA1700.</p>

      <div class="comparison-box">
        <div class="comp-col">
          <h3>AMD AM5</h3>
          <p>The newer platform. Its biggest advantage is longevity—AMD has promised support for several years, meaning you can likely upgrade your CPU later without buying a new motherboard. It requires DDR5 RAM and currently houses the reigning gaming champion: the Ryzen 7 7800X3D.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="comp-col">
          <h3>Intel LGA1700</h3>
          <p>A mature, stable platform supporting both 12th, 13th, and 14th Gen Intel CPUs. It offers flexibility as you can find motherboards that support either cheaper DDR4 or faster DDR5 RAM. However, it is at the end of its life cycle, meaning future CPU upgrades will require a new motherboard.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>4. Compatibility Checklist</h2>
      <p>Before hitting checkout, double-check these crucial compatibility points:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Does the CPU socket match the motherboard? (e.g., AM5 CPU requires an AM5 motherboard).</li>
        <li>Is the RAM supported by the motherboard? (DDR4 vs DDR5).</li>
        <li>Will the CPU cooler fit inside the case? (Check cooler height vs case clearance).</li>
        <li>Is the power supply wattage sufficient? (Use an online wattage calculator and add 20% headroom).</li>
        <li>Will the graphics card physically fit in the case? (Check GPU length vs case clearance).</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>5. Step-by-Step Build Process</h2>
      <p>Building a PC usually takes 2-4 hours for beginners. Work in a clean, well-lit area and avoid building on carpet to reduce static electricity risks.</p>

      <div class="build-steps">
        <div class="step">
          <h4>Step 1: Prep the Motherboard</h4>
          <p>Place your motherboard on its cardboard box. Install the CPU (ensure the gold triangle aligns with the socket), snap in your RAM sticks (usually slots 2 and 4), and install your M.2 NVMe SSD. It's much easier to do this outside the case.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="step">
          <h4>Step 2: Install the CPU Cooler</h4>
          <p>If using an air cooler, install it now. If using an AIO liquid cooler, you might just want to install the mounting bracket now and attach the pump later once the motherboard is in the case.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="step">
          <h4>Step 3: Prepare the Case</h4>
          <p>Remove the side panels. Install your power supply (PSU) and route the main cables to the back of the case. Install the motherboard I/O shield (if your motherboard doesn't have it pre-installed).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="step">
          <h4>Step 4: Mount the Motherboard</h4>
          <p>Carefully lower the motherboard into the case. Ensure it aligns with the standoffs and the I/O shield. Screw it in securely, but don't overtighten.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="step">
          <h4>Step 5: Wiring and Cable Management</h4>
          <p>Connect the 24-pin ATX power to the motherboard, the 8-pin EPS power to the top left for the CPU, and plug in your case fans. Connect the tiny, annoying front panel connectors (power switch, reset switch) using your motherboard manual as a guide. Route cables behind the motherboard tray for a clean look.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="step">
          <h4>Step 6: Install the GPU</h4>
          <p>Remove the necessary PCIe slot covers on the back of the case. Push the GPU into the top PCIe x16 slot until it clicks. Screw it into the case bracket to secure it, then plug in the necessary PCIe power cables from your PSU.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>6. BIOS Setup and OS Installation</h2>
      <p>The hard part is over! Now it's time to bring it to life.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Plug in your monitor (directly to the GPU, not the motherboard!), keyboard, and mouse. Turn on the power supply switch and hit the case power button.</li>
        <li>If it posts (shows a screen), tap DEL or F2 to enter the BIOS.</li>
        <li>In the BIOS, check that your CPU, RAM, and SSD are detected.</li>
        <li><strong>Crucial Step:</strong> Enable XMP (Intel) or EXPO/DOCP (AMD) to ensure your RAM runs at its advertised speed, not the slow default speed.</li>
        <li>Insert a USB flash drive with the Windows Installation Media. Save and exit the BIOS, and boot from the USB to install Windows.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>7. Drivers and Benchmarking</h2>
      <p>Once you are in Windows, run Windows Update multiple times until there are no updates left. Then, head to NVIDIA or AMD's website to download the latest graphics drivers. Avoid using third-party "driver updater" software.</p>
      <p>Finally, download a benchmarking tool like 3DMark or Cinebench, or simply load up a demanding game. Check your temperatures using software like HWMonitor or HWiNFO64 to ensure your CPU and GPU aren't overheating (aim for under 85°C under heavy load).</p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      {faqs.map(f => (
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>{f.q}</h3>
          <p>{f.a}</p>
        </div>
      ))}

    </section>
  </div>

  <style>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .hero p { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; max-width: 650px; margin: 0 auto; line-height: 1.5; }

    .content-section { margin-bottom: 3rem; }
    .content-section h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 1rem; margin-top: 2.5rem; }
    .content-section h3 { font-size: 1.3rem; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; margin-top: 1.5rem; }
    .content-section p { color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    .content-section ul { color: var(--text-secondary); margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.6; }
    .content-section li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }

    a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; }
    a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
    strong { color: var(--text-primary); }

    /* Tiers */
    .tier-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr)); gap: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    .tier-card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; }
    .tier-card.highlight { border: 2px solid var(--accent-color); position: relative; }
    .tier-card h3 { margin-top: 0; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .tier-card p { font-size: 0.95rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    .tier-card ul { padding-left: 1rem; margin: 0; font-size: 0.9rem; }
    .tier-card li { margin-bottom: 0.4rem; }

    /* Comparison Box */
    .comparison-box { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; background: var(--card-bg); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .comp-col h3 { margin-top: 0; }

    /* Build Steps */
    .build-steps { margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    .step { background: var(--card-bg); border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-color); padding: 1rem 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; border-radius: 0 8px 8px 0; }
    .step h4 { margin: 0 0 0.5rem; font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .step p { margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem; }

    /* FAQ */
    .faq-item { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 10px; padding: 1.2rem 1.5rem; margin: 1rem 0; }
    .faq-item h3 { margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .faq-item p { margin-bottom: 0; }

    @media (max-width: 600px) {
      .hero h1 { font-size: 1.6rem; }
      .comparison-box { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
